---
/**
 * ai-security/0001 · Figure 5 — "Plant now, fire later, on someone else"
 * (context poisoning).
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from the source lesson (figure + svg + figcaption incl. the
 * footnote <sup id="r5b">). Lives as an .astro component (kebab-case SVG attrs are
 * unreliable in MDX). The shared arwR arrowhead marker is embedded inline so the
 * figure renders standalone; the id matches the source DOM.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 640 200"
        role="img"
        aria-label="An attacker poisons a retrievable store now; the payload fires later on a different user's turn when it's retrieved into their context window."
    >
        <defs>
            <marker
                id="arwR"
                viewBox="0 0 10 10"
                refX="8.5"
                refY="5"
                markerWidth="7"
                markerHeight="7"
                orient="auto-start-reverse"
                ><path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 z" fill="#9a2417"></path></marker
            >
        </defs>
        <text x="320" y="18" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >Plant now, fire later, on someone else</text
        >
        <!-- t0 plant -->
        <rect
            x="28"
            y="44"
            width="160"
            height="56"
            rx="8"
            fill="#fbecec"
            stroke="#9a2417"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="108" y="62" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >T0 · attacker writes</text
        >
        <text x="108" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7.8" fill="#6b675f"
            >poisoned doc / memory</text
        >
        <text x="108" y="90" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7.8" fill="#6b675f"
            >entry / tool result</text
        >
        <line x1="188" y1="72" x2="244" y2="72" stroke="#9a2417" marker-end="url(#arwR)"></line>
        <!-- store -->
        <rect x="246" y="44" width="148" height="56" rx="8" fill="#eef2f7" stroke="#1f3a5a"></rect>
        <text x="320" y="66" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" font-weight="700" fill="#1f3a5a"
            >Retrievable store</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7.8" fill="#6b675f"
            >payload dormant &hellip;</text
        >
        <line x1="394" y1="72" x2="450" y2="72" stroke="#9a2417" marker-end="url(#arwR)"></line>
        <!-- t1 fire -->
        <rect
            x="452"
            y="44"
            width="160"
            height="56"
            rx="8"
            fill="#f1eef2"
            stroke="#b5179e"
            stroke-width="2"></rect>
        <text x="532" y="62" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" font-weight="700" fill="#b5179e"
            >T1 · victim's turn</text
        >
        <text x="532" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7.8" fill="#6b675f"
            >retrieved into a</text
        >
        <text x="532" y="90" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7.8" fill="#6b675f"
            >different user's window</text
        >
        <!-- contrast band -->
        <rect x="60" y="122" width="520" height="34" rx="6" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#b5179e"></rect>
        <text x="320" y="137" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" font-weight="700" fill="#b5179e"
            >Indirect injection fires on the request that retrieves it. Poisoning is planted now and
            fires later.</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="150" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >The time-and-tenant gap is the danger: write once, wait, hit everyone who ingests the
            source.</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" font-style="italic" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >Defense: control writes into retrievable stores · scope retrieval by ACL · bound the
            blast radius.</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        If your knowledge base ingests user uploads or scraped pages, assume it's poisoned. The
        question isn't whether a bad doc gets in — it's whether a bad doc can ever become a <em
            >candidate</em
        > for the wrong user.<sup><a href="#s2" id="r5b">2</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
